{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17617570","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17617570"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:15:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:15:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16477"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16477","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16477"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.04,0.6,0.04,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9168"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74914"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9168","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9168"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16477"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60412"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"279"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"6356"},{"type":"tags","id":"8094"},{"type":"tags","id":"8505"},{"type":"tags","id":"8506"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21771"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21774"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"74914","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/74914"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old female presents with sudden atraumatic blurring of vision and pain on eye movements. On further questioning, she also reports \u0027pins and needles\u0027 sensations in her arms. She has no previous medical history and is not on regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most common location for multiple sclerosis lesions on magnetic resonance imaging?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Basal ganglia","Cerebellar grey matter","Periventricular white matter","Temporal lobe cortex","Thalamus"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of multiple sclerosis (MS), including optic neuritis and sensory disturbance. MS is a demyelinating disease that predominantly affects white matter in characteristic locations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeriventricular white matter\u003C/strong\u003E is the most common location for MS lesions. These lesions typically appear as ovoid areas perpendicular to the ventricles, known as Dawson\u0027s fingers. The corpus callosum is frequently involved, with lesions best seen on sagittal fluid-attenuated inversion recovery (FLAIR) sequences.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasal ganglia\u003C/strong\u003E are deep grey matter structures that are rarely affected in MS. When deep grey matter is involved, it typically occurs late in the disease course.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellar grey matter\u003C/strong\u003E is not a typical location for MS lesions. While the cerebellum can be affected, lesions are more commonly found in cerebellar white matter tracts.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etemporal lobe cortex\u003C/strong\u003E, being grey matter, is not a characteristic location for MS lesions. MS predominantly affects white matter, though some cortical involvement can occur in advanced disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ethalamus\u003C/strong\u003E, like other deep grey matter structures, is not a common site for MS lesions. When present, thalamic involvement usually indicates advanced disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther common locations for MS lesions include the juxtacortical white matter, infratentorial regions (particularly the brainstem), and spinal cord. The presence of lesions disseminated in time and space is a key diagnostic criterion for MS.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Multiple sclerosis commonly affects periventricular white matter, particularly the corpus callosum.","Dawson\u0027s fingers are characteristic periventricular lesions extending outward from the ventricles.","The optic nerves, brainstem, and spinal cord are other common sites for multiple sclerosis lesions."],"references":["Seewann A, Vrenken H, van der Valk P, Blezer EL, Knol DL, Castelijns JA, Polman CH, Pouwels PJ, Barkhof F, Geurts JJ. Diffusely abnormal white matter in chronic multiple sclerosis: imaging and histopathologic analysis. Arch Neurol. 2009 May;66(5):601-9. doi: 10.1001/archneurol.2009.57. PMID: 19433660.","Lassmann H. Mechanisms of white matter damage in multiple sclerosis. Glia. 2014 Nov;62(11):1816-30. doi: 10.1002/glia.22597. Epub 2014 Jan 28. PMID: 24470325.","Vasileiou ES, Fitzgerald KC. Multiple Sclerosis Pathogenesis and Updates in Targeted Therapeutic Approaches. Curr Allergy Asthma Rep. 2023 Sep;23(9):481-496. doi: 10.1007/s11882-023-01102-0. Epub 2023 Jul 4. PMID: 37402064.","Dighriri IM, Aldalbahi AA, Albeladi F, Tahiri AA, Kinani EM, Almohsen RA, Alamoudi NH, Alanazi AA, Alkhamshi SJ, Althomali NA, Alrubaiei SN, Altowairqi FK. An Overview of the History, Pathophysiology, and Pharmacological Interventions of Multiple Sclerosis. Cureus. 2023 Jan 2;15(1):e33242. doi: 10.7759/cureus.33242. PMID: 36733554; PMCID: PMC9888604."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60412"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16477"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60412"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-28T10:17:24+10:30","updatedAt":"20